<!-- Hero -->
<section class="relative overflow-hidden min-h-[55vh] flex items-center">
  <img
    src="/P8675/images/aboutus-html-1.jpg"
    alt="View from Worldham Country Cattery over the wildlife garden towards East Worldham"
    class="absolute inset-0 w-full h-full object-cover"
    fetchpriority="high"
  />
  <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/60"></div>
  <div class="relative z-10 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-16 text-center text-white">
    <span class="inline-block bg-[#FEC600] text-[#4C3B00] text-sm font-700 px-4 py-1 rounded-full mb-4">📍 Alton, Hampshire</span>
    <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-800 text-white mb-4">About Us</h1>
    <p class="text-white/85 text-lg">The story of Worldham Country Cattery and the person behind it</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- About Sarah -->
<section class="py-20 px-4 bg-[#FFFCF2]">
  <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-start">
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-800 text-[#4C3B00] mb-6">Meet Sarah Moore</h2>
      <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Worldham Country Cattery is owned and run by Sarah Moore, in the garden of her home in East Worldham.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Sarah qualified as a veterinary surgeon in July 1990 from the Royal Veterinary College, London and worked initially in Alton and Oxford in mixed practice.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed mb-4">
        In 1993 she started working in small animal practice in Farnham and Aldershot where she spent the last 25 years of her veterinary career.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Sarah has had a long-held ambition to run her own cattery and believes her veterinary experience enhances the care she can provide to guests in this state-of-the-art facility.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed mb-4">
        She has undertaken a cattery management course recommended by International Cat Care and continues to keep updated with all things feline.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed">
        Worldham Country Cattery is licenced by East Hampshire District Council and fully insured with Cliverton.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-2xl shadow-lg">
        <img
          src="/P8675/images/aboutus-html-2.jpg"
          alt="The cattery grounds at Worldham"
          class="w-full object-cover"
          width="590"
          height="445"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>
      <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-2xl shadow-lg">
        <img
          src="/P8675/images/aboutus-html-4.jpg"
          alt="View from the cattery towards East Worldham"
          class="w-full object-cover"
          width="482"
          height="271"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Caption from original site -->
<section class="py-8 px-4 bg-[#FFFAEB]">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
    <p class="text-[#987700] italic text-sm">View from the cattery over the wildlife garden, under construction, towards the village of East Worldham</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- The Build Story -->
<section class="py-20 px-4 bg-[#FFFCF2]">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-800 text-[#4C3B00] mb-4 text-center">How We Got Here</h2>
    <p class="text-[#987700] text-center mb-12">The story of planning, building, and opening Worldham Country Cattery</p>

    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div class="flex gap-5">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-[#FEC600] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-800 text-[#4C3B00] text-sm">2017</div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-700 text-[#4C3B00] mb-2">The ambition takes shape</h3>
          <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed text-sm">
            For several years Sarah had an ambition to open her own cattery in the beautiful surroundings of North East Hampshire. She looked at various cattery manufacturers and decided on a modern uPVC construction. In November 2017 she contacted Peticular Pens in Ipswich and asked them to plan a cattery for up to 20 cats with 6 double and 2 family suites, an isolation suite and a kitchen/reception facility.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-5">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-[#FEC600] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-800 text-[#4C3B00] text-sm">Dec</div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-700 text-[#4C3B00] mb-2">A visit to Nottingham</h3>
          <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed text-sm">
            In December 2017 Sarah travelled to Nottingham to see a successful cattery by Peticular. She was struck by the light airy feel, the provision of various shelves within the suites, and the digital environmental control within the sleeping area. She particularly liked the window in the top of the sleeping area allowing cats interest even when the weather meant they preferred to stay in the warm. The design also included acrylic sheets in the mesh windows of the safety corridor, keeping out the wind and rain.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-5">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-[#FEC600] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-800 text-[#4C3B00] text-sm">2018</div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-700 text-[#4C3B00] mb-2">Planning permission</h3>
          <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed text-sm">
            The first hurdle was a pre-planning meeting with East Hampshire District Council on 8 February 2018. It went well – another uPVC cattery within the South Downs National Park had received consent in 2017, so the outlook was positive. Following considerable preparation of a planning statement, the application was submitted online on 28 August and validated on 17 September. The local Parish Council supported the application at their October meeting, and planning permission was granted on 14 November 2018.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-5">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-[#FEC600] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-800 text-[#4C3B00] text-sm">2019</div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-700 text-[#4C3B00] mb-2">The build begins</h3>
          <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed text-sm">
            Work on the base began on 13 February 2019. The base was completed in early March and on 10 March, Peticular Pens arrived from Ipswich to construct the cattery. Despite the appalling weather in the first week, the build went very well and was finished on time and on budget on 22 March.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-5">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-[#FEC600] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-800 text-[#4C3B00] text-sm">Apr</div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-700 text-[#4C3B00] mb-2">Electrics, tiling and fitting out</h3>
          <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed text-sm">
            Electrical work started on 10 April – a larger job than expected, with infrared heaters, extractors, lights and sockets for all 9 suites and the kitchen/reception. Work finished by Easter. Tiling started on 6 May and was completed in a week, producing a beautiful finish. The kitchen was then installed and equipment ordered: beds, litter trays, scratch posts and more.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-5">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-[#FEC600] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-800 text-[#4C3B00] text-sm">Jun</div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-700 text-[#4C3B00] mb-2">Licensed and open</h3>
          <p class="text-[#4C3B00] leading-relaxed text-sm">
            On 9 June the licence application was submitted to EHDC environmental health department. The inspection on 19 June went well, the licence was granted, and Worldham Country Cattery was finally open.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Additional image -->
